## Learned Workspace Facts

- TypeScript Cmd+Click into node_modules requires registering bundled `.d.ts` at the path tsserver actually probes (`file:///node_modules/<pkg>/…`) AND a workspace provider unifying hover defs + go-to-defs in one source.
- The `node_modules` FS mount is the canonical location for reading bundled API `.d.ts` source — agent reads against this mount are intentional and resolve through the FileService mount table.
- Monaco IntelliSense types: `libs/api-extractor` generates bundled `.d.ts` per kernel; `TypeAcquisitionService` registers them via `addExtraLib` at `file:///node_modules/<pkg>/index.d.ts`; custom declarations for opencascade.js live in `repos/opencascade.js/src/declarations/`; OCJS Doxygen → JSDoc → Monaco rendering is owned entirely by the Python emitter in `repos/opencascade.js/src/` (token normalisation, list-item bullet formatting, sentence-truncation prevention) — never patch JSDoc strings in JavaScript; `dts-validation.test.ts`-style file-content assertions on the generated `.d.ts` are preferred over CI-only checks for namespace removal, `any` count, and bullet/typedoc presence; Monaco LSP activation is lazy and extension-driven — register language workers/grammars on demand when a file extension matching the LSP first appears in the monaco model list (vscode `onLanguage` activation pattern), never eagerly at editor mount; KCL LSP must not load when only TS-based kernels (replicad/opencascade) are open; nested JSON colorization mirrors VSCode's algorithm — **brackets cycle every 3 levels, keys cycle every 7 levels**, bracket colors must NEVER collide with primitive colors (true/false/null = light blue, numbers/strings keep base palette), and adjacent key/value vs bracket pairs must always render in different colors so the leading bracket before a key is visually distinct (single-color "flat" output is the smoking-gun bug); resolve all colors from the active Shiki theme (no hardcoded hex), prefer TextMate contributions over monkey-patching the JSON tokenizer; new Shiki/TextMate languages (e.g. SysML v2 from `repos/sensmetry-sysml-2ls`, KCL, STL) are added by cloning the upstream grammar via `pnpm repos`, generating a precompiled Shiki bundle through the forked `repos/shiki` build, registering under `apps/ui/app/lib/<lang>-language/` (mirroring `stl-language` shape), wiring into the Monaco language registry, and capturing the workflow in the `add-monaco-language` skill; Monaco language contributions that need workspace FS access (KCL today, OpenSCAD/Python/Rust next) share **one canonical FS bridge** modelled on VS Code Web's `*-language-features` pattern — protocol package at `libs/lsp-fs` (`@taucad/lsp-fs/protocol`: `fs/stat`, `fs/readDir`, `fs/content`, `fs/findFiles` requests + `FileType` enum + `encodeFsContentWire`), Monaco-side bridge package at `libs/lsp` (`@taucad/lsp`) hosting `serveLanguageFileSystem` in `language-fs-bridge.ts`, in-process JSON-RPC plumbing (`in-process-jsonrpc.ts`), `monaco-lsp-binding.ts`, and the `monaco-uri-workspace.ts` URI normaliser; every LSP worker spawned by a contribution receives `{ port, filePoolBuffer? }` exactly the same way the runtime kernel worker does today via `client.connect({ port, filePoolBuffer })` — three-tier read pipeline: Tier 0 `SharedPool.resolveCopy(path)` zero-IPC (~10ns warm), Tier 1 bridge `MessagePort` RPC to the FM worker (~1ms async, populates the pool as a side effect), Tier 2 `Atomics.wait` SAB request slot via `libs/lsp-fs/src/sync/` (`sync-fs-protocol.ts`/`sync-fs-client.ts`/`sync-fs-server.ts`: Int32Array request slot + bounded content arena + `Atomics.wait`/`Atomics.notify`, the FM worker hosts the server side); never preload the workspace up front and never reinvent the bridge per language; full design in `docs/research/scalable-language-contribution-fs-architecture.md`. JS/TS specifically uses a **custom Monaco TS worker** (`libs/lsp/src/monaco-ts-worker/` — `tau-sync-ts-worker.ts` subclasses `TypeScriptWorker`, `monaco-ts-worker.entry.ts` is the worker entrypoint) per Monaco PR #3488 (microsoft/monaco-editor#3488, merged 0.55.x) which exports `initialize`/`ts`/`TypeScriptWorker`/`libFileMap` from `monaco-editor/esm/vs/language/typescript/ts.worker.js` so authors can subclass + call `initialize(...)` from a module worker — the legacy `customWorkerPath`/`importScripts` mechanism does NOT work in module workers. The subclass overrides `LanguageServiceHost` FS methods (`readFile`, `fileExists`, `directoryExists`, `getScriptVersion`) to consult `SharedPool` + the sync-FS Tier 2 slot instead of relying on Monaco's eager model mirror, replacing the prior `MonacoModelService.syncAllInBackground` lazy-tree preload (which only saw directories explicitly walked by `treeService.listDirectory()`, leaving unexpanded subdirs invisible — Z1 in `monaco-typescript-intellisense-investigation.md`); when the eager preloader is still in use it MUST drive off the worker-side complete index via `proxy.getDirectoryStat('')` (the same source the search index uses), NOT the lazy main-thread `treeService.getTreeSnapshot()`. TS module resolution gotchas: third-party packages registered via `addExtraLib` at `file:///node_modules/<pkg>/index.d.ts` only resolve when the host's virtual `directoryExists` derives `node_modules/<pkg>` synthetic directories from extraLib paths — TS's Node resolution algorithm checks `directoryExists` before following into the package, so a missing virtual dir blocks resolution even when `readFile` would succeed; `addExtraLib` content with `prewrapped: true` flag must be wrapped in `declare module '<pkg>' { ... }` (raw api-extractor output is NOT prewrapped — ambient module wrapping happens at the registration site); `compilerOptions.moduleResolution` MUST be `NodeNext` or `Bundler` (not `NodeJs`) so `.js` import specifiers rewrite to the `.ts` source on Cmd+Click and module resolution; lib-file (`lib.esnext.d.ts` etc.) versioning falls through `super.getScriptVersion()` returning empty — the override must short-circuit any path where `_getScriptText` has content but the upstream version is empty by returning a static version like `"1"`.
